WEBVTT

00:00.031 --> 00:01.012
This is down here.

00:01.994 --> 00:11.528
It goes in and the first thing they do is they normalize the text and they transform it into phonemes, which is you can do this in a deterministic fashion.

00:11.568 --> 00:13.631
There are scripts that do this.

00:14.052 --> 00:16.656
This is the only pre-processing they do.

00:17.637 --> 00:21.323
And they can also leave it away in the Heaven Ablation on their website.

00:21.343 --> 00:25.549
So this is like phoneme text, cat sat on the mat.

00:25.529 --> 00:33.267
Now, this phoneme text goes through these big block of convolutions and of dilated convolutions.

00:33.808 --> 00:40.584
And this outputs a 200 Hertz representation token length alignment.

00:41.005 --> 00:42.829
Okay, I should specify this.

00:42.809 --> 00:48.418
So for each token here, it outputs a length.

00:48.939 --> 00:52.825
So this thing predicts the length of each of the tokens.

00:53.426 --> 01:01.179
These, all of this, all of this thing here is to, um, to embed the tokens in hidden space and then predict its length.

01:01.800 --> 01:06.708
You can see that right here.

01:07.629 --> 01:07.870
Okay.

01:08.691 --> 01:09.913
So first,

01:11.446 --> 01:23.061
We use F to, to take X. So F is a stack of dilated convolutions and it takes X and outputs a hidden representation.

01:23.281 --> 01:33.775
So H. So first X goes to H and then H is used to predict L and L is the length of that token.

01:35.847 --> 01:40.556
So we embed this into a hidden representation with this right here.

01:41.157 --> 01:45.385
And then we use this stack to predict the length of each token.

01:45.485 --> 01:54.582
So this could be, this could say something like this cat token right here is 20 milliseconds long or

01:54.562 --> 01:58.908
Instead of milliseconds, you would use something like frames or data points.

01:59.429 --> 02:04.877
Maybe this is 200 data points long.

02:05.478 --> 02:07.061
And then SAT is a bit shorter.

02:07.081 --> 02:08.503
So this is 100 long.

02:08.963 --> 02:10.285
And ON is really short.

02:10.325 --> 02:11.647
So this is 50 long.

02:12.088 --> 02:14.832
So for each token, it predicts the length.

02:14.812 --> 02:21.603
So now if we have the length of each, we can sort of calculate where the starting point is.

02:21.984 --> 02:31.740
So if we want to know, if we know that here is the beginning and the beginning of the sentence, we conservatively assume that there is

02:31.720 --> 02:41.239
So they give some silence buffer here, but roughly you can assume that the beginning of the speech corresponds to the first token.

02:41.259 --> 02:47.451
You can simply trace the waveform and whenever it goes up, that's where the first token starts.

02:47.431 --> 02:59.436
So then, since we know that's where the first token starts, and if we could predict the length of each one correctly, we could simply sum those up to figure out where our word starts.

02:59.456 --> 03:07.633
So if we want to know where on starts, we simply go from the beginning and go 200 plus 100 milliseconds or data points.

03:07.613 --> 03:13.464
200 plus 100, here is where on starts, okay.

03:14.205 --> 03:20.918
And if we want to figure out the middle of on, we simply add the half of this number.

03:21.258 --> 03:24.625
So plus 25 gets you to the middle.

03:24.665 --> 03:31.377
So this is, this here is the center of the token on.

03:32.335 --> 03:48.100
So for each token, we predict the length like this and thereby we can just calculate for each one by summing up from the beginning and then adding half of its own length where the center of that token in the entire sequence is.

03:48.080 --> 03:58.536
Okay, now we do this, we said we take random two second audio, but we do this procedure for the entire text.

03:58.857 --> 04:13.480
Okay, for every single token in the text that we look at, so in the 20 second text, we do this because then for each token, we'll get a token center.

04:13.460 --> 04:19.774
and now the aligners job here is to align that to the actual sound.

04:21.442 --> 04:49.693
so what we also give the generators here the offset so let's say we have this twenty second of speech and we randomly sampled these two seconds and that's maybe five seconds from the beginning we also tell it this is five seconds right here so what we can now do is we can calculate back sort of and and say okay here i have

04:49.673 --> 05:01.730
I first need to discard five seconds of my signal, and I have a prediction how long each token is, so I can just cross out tokens until I have basically wasted five seconds.

05:02.471 --> 05:13.487
And then I know, okay, from here to wherever these things sum up to two seconds, from here to that, those are my two seconds that I want to look at.

05:13.467 --> 05:20.216
Now, this is how I figure out where in the big sound wave my fragment is.

05:21.238 --> 05:28.548
Because I have this offset where I sampled it, and I simply use this and the predicted lengths to figure it out.

05:28.968 --> 05:34.536
Now I still need to figure out these tokens that are actually in the span, how do they distribute?

05:35.417 --> 05:37.720
And that's what this aligner here does.

05:37.700 --> 05:57.104
Since we've already predicted the token centers, we simply assume that if these are correct, right, then if this is, let's say, if this is one second long, I assume that the middle is after 0.5 seconds or this is one second, the middle is 0.5 seconds.

05:57.124 --> 06:00.869
So I think that this token is aligned right here.

06:01.529 --> 06:03.572
This is the center of the token.

06:03.552 --> 06:11.086
Now, we want to be a little bit fuzzy with respect to that.

06:11.667 --> 06:16.756
So what they do is they sort of use a Gaussian kernel right here.

06:16.796 --> 06:23.027
So for each token, as you can see here, each token has a center, which is here.

06:23.127 --> 06:27.535
So the y-axis is the time in sound and the x-axis is the token.

06:27.515 --> 06:31.619
And for each token, we say, well, it doesn't have to be exactly there.

06:32.040 --> 06:36.024
It can be, so they put a Gaussian kernel like this.

06:36.645 --> 06:43.151
Okay, if you imagine this kernel popping out of the frame, they say this is about where the center is.

06:43.472 --> 06:52.902
And for this token right here, they say, well, it's probably here in the middle, but it could also be here, or here, or here, or here.

06:53.442 --> 06:57.066
And we wait this like this.

06:57.046 --> 07:04.014
So these are the weights and then you simply sum up the weights with these embeddings.

07:04.915 --> 07:20.472
So for each token out of this dilated convolution block you get a hidden embedding and by using this alignment matrix that you computed by predicting the lengths and therefore predicting the centers of the tokens you can then

07:20.452 --> 07:21.834
sort of shift.

07:22.034 --> 07:31.264
So first, you assume that h1, h2, h3, if you were to do nothing, these would just all take up like a third of the time.

07:31.284 --> 07:49.986
And now by multiplying with this matrix, you have the opportunity, because you predicted a longer length for the first token, you have the opportunity to shift that a bit to the right, and maybe shorten the second token a bit, and then the third token goes until the end.

07:49.966 --> 07:52.689
Okay, that's what this aligner thing is.

07:53.049 --> 07:54.751
This is not a model by itself.

07:55.192 --> 08:00.037
All that this takes in is the computation right here of the token lengths.

08:00.197 --> 08:03.801
This estimates these token lengths for each of the tokens.

08:04.161 --> 08:05.843
And the rest is deterministic.

08:05.863 --> 08:08.846
It's simply saying, okay, how much is the offset?

08:09.307 --> 08:09.587
Cool.

08:10.067 --> 08:12.270
That's how we know where in the sound wave we are.

08:12.610 --> 08:15.113
And then where is each of the centers?

08:15.273 --> 08:18.977
And we simply do that by summing up the predicted token lengths.

08:18.957 --> 08:27.478
And then we use a Gaussian kernel with like a set hyper parameter to be a little bit fuzzy with respect to these lengths right here.

08:27.599 --> 08:29.443
So to be differentiable basically.

08:30.065 --> 08:36.561
And that will, that will ultimately train this loss, this model right here that computes the token lengths.

08:38.110 --> 08:45.758
So we sum up in a weighted fashion these embeddings right here, and that's what goes into the generator.

08:45.778 --> 08:55.849
So now we have embeddings and we have the alignments for the embeddings, which are these pieces of where in the sound wave these are.

08:56.289 --> 09:01.975
And from that, the generator can now produce the sound wave itself.

09:01.955 --> 09:04.522
And that's basically, that's just an up sampling here.

09:04.642 --> 09:13.345
I think that's just an up convolution, um, up sampling from 200 Hertz signal to a 24 kilohertz signal.

09:17.415 --> 09:17.676
Cool.

09:18.338 --> 09:18.799
So.

